    "The objective of Task 1 is to calculate the average rating received by each movie based on all user ratings recorded in the MovieLens 100K dataset. Using Apache Spark SQL, the ratings dataset was joined with the movie metadata, and the average rating (AVG) together with the total number of ratings (COUNT) was computed for every movie. The query produced 1,682 records which corresponds exactly to the total number of movies stored in the MovieLens dataset. This result is further validated in Apache Cassandra, where the task1_average_ratings table contains 1,682 rows confirming that the analytical results were successfully written into the NoSQL database without any data loss.\n",
    "\n",
    "The analysis indicates that several movies achieved a perfect average rating of 5.0. Examples include Prefontaine (1997) and Star Kid (1997) each receiving three ratings while several other movies also obtained an average rating of 5.0 but were evaluated by only one or two users. Although these movies appear at the top of the ranking, the accompanying total_ratings attribute reveals that their high scores are based on a relatively small number of observations. Consequently, the average rating alone should not be interpreted as a definitive indicator of overall movie quality or popularity. From a data analytics perspective, a larger number of ratings generally provides greater statistical reliability because it reflects the opinions of a broader user population and reduces the influence of individual ratings."
