   "source": [
    "Task 3 aims to identify active users who have rated at least 50 movies and determine their favourite movie genre based on the highest frequency of genres among the movies they have rated. This behavioural profiling was performed using Apache Spark SQL by aggregating user rating histories joining them with movie genre information and ranking the genres according to their occurrence for each user. The analytical results were subsequently stored in the task3_favourite_genres table within Apache Cassandra. The validation query SELECT COUNT(*) confirms that the table contains 568 records indicating that 568 users satisfied the predefined criterion of rating at least 50 movies. This demonstrates that the filtering, aggregation and ranking operations were successfully executed and that the processed results were correctly stored in Cassandra. The warning message stating \"Aggregation query used without partition key\" is a standard Cassandra notification for full table aggregation queries and does not affect the accuracy or integrity of the stored results.\n",
    "\n",
    "The analytical output reveals that highly active users exhibit clear genre preferences based on their historical rating behaviour. For example, the most active user (User ID 405) who rated 737 movies has Drama as the favourite genre with 309 rated drama movies. Similarly, other highly active users including User IDs 655, 13, 450 and 276 also demonstrate a strong preference for the Drama genre suggesting that drama is one of the dominant genres among frequent users in the MovieLens dataset. From a data science perspective, this type of behavioural analysis provides valuable insights for developing personalised recommendation systems, customer segmentation and preference modelling. By understanding users' favourite genres through their historical interactions, recommendation algorithms can generate more relevant movie suggestions thereby improving user satisfaction and engagement. The successful identification of 568 active users further illustrates the capability of Apache Spark SQL to perform complex user profiling tasks efficiently while leveraging Apache Cassandra as a scalable NoSQL database for persistent storage and subsequent analytical applications."
   ]
